24. Equations for the inverse problem

The next step is to derive equations for $\mu (x, \cdot )$ on $(\Sigma \backslash 0)\cup Z$ which correspond to (21.8) and (21.9). In view of (24.27), Lemma23.3, and the fact

24.28 $$\begin{equation} \mathbf{1}P(\cdot )=\mathbf{1}, \cssId{texmlid537}{\tag{24.28}} \end{equation}$$

we obtain

24.29 $$\begin{align} \mu (x, z & )(I-w_{x}^{-}(z))P_{-}(z)=\mu _{-}(x, z)P_{-}(z)\cssId{texmlid230}{\tag{24.29}}\\ & =\mathbf{1}\ +(C_{-}(\mu (x, \cdot )w_{x}(\cdot )P_{-}(\cdot )))(z)+\sum _{j}(z-z_{j})^{-1}\mu (x,z_{j})v_{x}(z_{j})P(z_{j})\\ & =\{\mathbf{1}+C_{+}(\mu (x, \cdot )w_{x}^{-}(\cdot )P_{-}(\cdot ))+C_{-}(\mu (x,\cdot )w_{x}^{+}(\cdot )P_{-}(\cdot ))\}(z)\\ &\quad +\{C_{-}(\mu (x, \cdot )w_{x}^{-}(\cdot )P_{-}(\cdot ))-C_{+}(\mu (x, \cdot )w_{x}^{-}(\cdot )P_{-}(\cdot ))\}(z)\\ &\quad +\sum _{j}(z-z_{j})^{-1}\mu (x, z_{j})v_{x}(z_{j})P(z_{j})\\ &=\{1+(C_{w,x}(\mu (x, \cdot )))(z)+\sum _{j}(z-z_{j})^{-1}\mu (x,z_{j})v_{x}(z_{j})P(z_{j}, z)\}P_{-}(z)\\ &\quad -\mu (x, z)w_{x}^{-}(z)P_{-}(z), \end{align}$$

where $C_{w, x}$ is defined for $\mathbf{C}^{n}$-valued functions on $\Sigma \backslash 0$ by

24.30 $$\begin{align} (C_{w,x}f)(z)& =(C_{+}(f(\cdot )w_{x}^{-}(\cdot )P(\cdot , z)))(z)\cssId{texmlid538}{\tag{24.30}}\\ &\quad +(C_{-}(f(\cdot )w_{x}^{+}(\cdot )P(\cdot , z)))(z). \end{align}$$

Thus (24. 29) gives

24.31 $$\begin{align} \mu (x, z)& =\mathbf{1}\ +(C_{w,x}(\mu (x, \cdot )))(z)\cssId{texmlid209}{\tag{24.31}}\\ &\qquad +\sum _{j}(z-z_{j})^{-1}\mu (x, z_{j})v_{x}(z_{j})P(z_{j},z). \end{align}$$

As $z\rightarrow z_{k}\in Z$,

$$\begin{align*} \mu (x, z)-(z-z_{k})^{-1}& \mu (x,z_{k})v_{x}(z_{k})\\ &\rightarrow \mathbf{1}+\int _{\Sigma }(\zeta -z_{k})^{-1}\mu (x,\zeta )w_{x}(\zeta )P(\zeta ,z)\frac{d_{\zeta }}{2\pi i}\\ &\quad \quad +\sum _{j\pm k}(z_{k}-z_{j})^{-1}\mu (x,z_{j})v_{x}(z_{j})P(z_{j},z_{k}), \end{align*}$$

where we have again used $P(z_{k}, z_{k})=1$. By (24.9), we now obtain

24.32 $$\begin{align} \mu (x, z_{k})= & 1+\int _{\Sigma }(\zeta -z_{k})^{-1}\mu (x,\zeta )w_{x}(\zeta )P(\zeta ,z_{k})\frac{d_{\zeta }}{2\pi i}\cssId{texmlid210}{\tag{24.32}}\\ & +\sum _{j\pm k}(z_{k}-z_{j})^{-1}\mu (x, z_{j})v_{x}(z_{j})P(z_{j}, z_{k}). \end{align}$$

Equations (24.31) and (24.32) determine $\mu (x, z),\ z\in (\Sigma \backslash 0)\cup Z$. As noted in the proof of Proposition (24.26), we also have

24.33 $$\begin{equation} \sum _{k}\left(\lim _{{\zeta \rightarrow 0}\atop {\zeta \in \Sigma _{k}}}(\mu (x, \zeta )w_{x}(\zeta )P_{-}(\zeta ))\right)=0. \cssId{texmlid247}{\tag{24.33}} \end{equation}$$

Finally, since $\mu (x, \alpha z)=\mu (x,z)$ for $z\in \mathbf{C}\backslash \Sigma$, we must have

24.34 $$\begin{equation} \mu (x, \alpha z)=\mu (x,z),\qquad z\in \Sigma \backslash 0. \cssId{texmlid231}{\tag{24.34}} \end{equation}$$

and

24.35 $$\begin{equation} \mu (x,\alpha z_{j})=\mu (x,z_{j}),\qquad z_{j}\in Z. \cssId{texmlid227}{\tag{24.35}} \end{equation}$$

The proof of Proposition24.36 also proves the following.

We have shown in this section that the problem of constructing a normalized eigenvector for $S_{x}$ is reduced to producing a solution of (24.31)(24.35). This is done in the following sections, by transforming the system (24.31)(24.35) into a Fredholm equation of index zero. Surjectivity then follows from injectivity, which follows in turn from Proposition 24.38 above. (Note that because of the behavior of $v(z)$ near $z=0$, the operator $I-C_{w,x}$ is not necessarily Fredholm, although $C_{w,x}$ is bounded.)

Converse of Proposition 24.38. Suppose $h(\cdot )$ is a null vector for $S_{x}$. Then the extension of $h(\cdot )$ to $(\Sigma \backslash 0)\cup Z$ via

$$\begin{equation*} h(z)\equiv h_{-}(z)(a_{x}^{-}(z))^{-1},\qquad z\in \Sigma \backslash 0, \tag*{$(24.8)^{\prime }$} \end{equation*}$$

$$\begin{equation*} h(z_{j})\displaystyle \equiv \lim _{z\rightarrow z_{j}}[h(z)-{\mathrm{Res}}[h;z_{j}]/(z-z_{j})],\qquad z_{j}\in Z, \tag*{$(24.9)^{\prime }$} \end{equation*}$$ satisfies (24.31)$'$(24.35)$'$.
